                                            <h3>﻿Unveiling the Vasari Corridor</h3>
                                            <p>Commissioned by Duke Cosimo I de' Medici in 1564 and designed by the legendary architect Giorgio Vasari, the corridor was conceived as a secure passageway for the ruling family, connecting the Palazzo Vecchio with the Palazzo Pitti across the Arno River. Winding above the bustling streets and the iconic Ponte Vecchio, it served as a private walkway, adorned with artworks and offering spectacular views, ensuring the Medici could move freely and safely in their city. The Vasari Corridor is a masterpiece of engineering and art, embodying the ambition and the sophistication of its creators.</p>

